04945nam a22008775i 9780814708828DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147088287 a10.18574/97808147088282doi  a(DE-B1597)547284  a(OCoLC)194299706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.0122200aPolitical Contingency :bStudying the Unexpected, the Accidental, and the Unforeseen /cIan Shapiro, Sonu Bedi. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Contingency's Challenge to Political Science -- t1. From Fortune to Feedback: Contingency and the Birth of Modern Political Science -- t2. Mapping Contingency -- t3. Resilience as the Explanandum of Social Theory -- t4. Events as Causes: The Case of American Politics -- t5. Contingent Public Policies and Racial Hierarchy: Lessons from Immigration and Census Policies -- t6. Region, Contingency, and Democratization -- t7. Contingency, Politics, and the Nature of Inquiry: Why Non-Events Matter -- t8. Modeling Contingency -- t9. When Democracy Complicates Peace: How Democratic Contingencies Affect Negotiated Settlements -- t10. Contingency in Biophysical Research -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistory is replete with instances of what might, or might not, have been. By calling something contingent, at a minimum we are saying that it did not have to be as it is. Things could have been otherwise, and they would have been otherwise if something had happened differently. This collection of original essays examines the significance of contingency in the study of politics. That is, how to study unexpected, accidental, or unknowable political phenomena in a systematic fashion. Yitzhak Rabin is assassinated. Saddam Hussein invades Kuwait. Hurricane Katrina hits New Orleans. How might history be different had these events not happened? How should social scientists interpret the significance of these events and can such unexpected outcomes be accounted for in a systematic way or by theoretical models? Can these unpredictable events be predicted for? Political Contingency addresses these and other related questions, providing theoretical and historical perspectives on the topic, empirical case studies, and the methodological challenges that the fact of contingency poses for the study of politics.Contributors: Sonu Bedi, Traci Burch, Jennifer L. Hochschild, Gregory A. Huber, Courtney Jung, David R. Mayhew, Philip Pettit, Andreas Schedler, Mark R. Shulman, Robert G. Shulman, Ian Shapiro, Susan Stokes, Elisabeth Jean Wood, and David Wootton  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCausationxPolitical aspects. 0aImaginary histories. 0aPolitical sciencexMethodology. 0aWorld politicsy1989- 4aThat. 4aThis. 4aaccidental. 4acollection. 4acontingency. 4aessays. 4aexamines. 4afashion. 4aoriginal. 4aphenomena. 4apolitical. 4apolitics. 4asignificance. 4astudy. 4asystematic. 4aunexpected. 4aunknowable. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBedi, Sonu, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShapiro, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814708828423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814708828.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEB